We went on a spontaneous bivalve binge and sat at their rear oyster bar. Our northern selections; Dodge Cove - Maine, Cabot Beach - Prince Edward Island, and Chelsea Gem & Pickering Pass - Washington - were presented well, served with several accompaniments, and hit the spot. They were refreshing and tasty, with nice body and brine. Minor issues; the oyster bar stools weren't comfortable - we were forewarned - and their Pearl Cup cocktail had too much vegetation, almost resulted in 4 stars. But having the bar open with outdoor service early in January with a full wolf moon is a hoot. It's a little weird but most enjoyable.

With a small outdoor/indoor bar in front, table seating throughout, and an oyster bar in the back, this spot can accommodate most any interest for someone looking for some truly excellent seafood. I walked up without a reservation in the evening on a Friday, and the bar was bustling, tables were full, but I was able to be seated immediately at the oyster bar, overlooking the fresh selections and work of the shuckers. With ten varieties of fresh oysters available, I was thrilled to have the chance to have one of each to find my favorites. Their house sauces were great too, each with their own delicate flavors that compliment the east/west coast oysters well. The house shrimp cocktail was also heavenly, and being able to choose the number of shrimp made for a perfect sized portion. The key lime pie finished off the meal without being too sour or too filling. Friendly company at the oyster bar, superb service, and an outstanding meal. I look back on my meal here with great appreciation and look forward to the next chance to return.

If you go, don’t be fooled by the overflowing crowd into the sidewalk in the bar side of the restaurant. I thought it would be an hour wait, but pushed past the crowd to find that I was seated immediately (there’s an entrance to avoid the bar, so you don’t have to push past).  Service: The server Nick was a true professional. He was friendly and extremely knowledgeable and was able to make great menu recommendations.  He even observed how fast we were eating to ensure that our entrees came out at the appropriate time when we finished our appetizers.  Appetizers: The muscles with the grilled bread appetizer is absolutely awesome! I would take a bowl of the broth alone as a soup. Also, a half pound is more than enough for two people. The braised pork cheek also is also amazing; tender and comes with delicious grits and fried onion straws for texture. We also ordered a dozen oysters on the half and again, perfect. Fresh, great texture, and delicious flavor.  Entre: I got the grilled blackened Mahi Mahi with fritters and jambalaya. It was cooked perfectly with the right amount of spice and kick to it. The jambalaya was flavorful and balanced perfectly, not overwhelmed by the pork sausage or peppers; savory and just enough sweet. Those fritters are the also just the right amount of starch to make you feel like you’re getting a well-rounded meal. No complaints at all.  Conclusion: I come out once a year for a conference and will be making this a must have each trip. Come here and eat! I’m not recommending, I’m telling you. You will thank me later and if you do come here because of my review I EXPECT you to thank me later. Haha! Jk

We visited with 5 friends from work. We got in and ordered a first round of drinks. One friend picked up the tab. For the second round, another one picked up the tab. When most had left, the bar man came to us claiming that there was over $20 left (5 Happy Hour drinks) on the tab. We told him that was a joke - we paid everything, it would mean that HALF of our tab hadn't been paid. We even went over the total order - the two rounds added together - and explained which person ordered what drinks. We had paid for all of our drinks. Also - the place asked for a credit card before opening up any tab, but when we asked: "What card did you put these drinks on?" (to determine which colleague might have already paid for it), he said that there was no card - it was "on the group" - even though for any drinks we had either paid immediately OR gave a card. So either the bar man is screwing us over OR someone put drinks on "our tab" (bar man could not remember who ordered these drinks). He would not let us leave. In the end he offered to take "one water of the bill", like it's about that one drink. What a nightmare - DON'T GO HERE!

The service tonight was really suffering and she didnt know the menu or ingredients very well but everybody has bad days...the manager made it right which is what counts. The kitchen did pretty well working with our food intolerances...my husband mentioned that besides seafood, there were not a whole lot of meat options, especially ones that weren't fried. He had the steak with blue cheese crumble with mashed potatoes and green beans...classic combo but the steak was not infused with flavor, most of the flavor was around the steak. I had the seafood gumbo which was divine!! We had four appetizers and my favorite was the Tchoupitoulas oysters...really great! The pictures on google are a bit misleading but aside from ambiance, I think what would have made me "favorite" this location for one of my regular eating choices is if they fried in rice bran oil rather than canola. Canola is not a healthy option and for anyone educated on healthy ingredients, rice bran oil would eliminate concern on over half of the menu options and make it more convenient to order unrestricted...which also makes it easier on the wait staff. Thanks for the Gumbo- it was to die for.

I've had my eye on this place for a while and was excited to finally come and partake of the cuisine. We started with the barbeque shrimp and Lobster rangoons. The lobster rangoons were very good and we were disappointed we received an odd number, we didn't want to share. The barbeque shrimp I definitely would not describe as barbeque. I expected grilled shrimp with housemade barbeque sauce but it just tasted like old bay seasoning with a lot of oil. They were very greasy. The bread was saturated in grease and I feel like I ate a pound of oil. We were less than impressed with our entrees. The fried shrimp were lacking flavor. The batter used to fry them had no seasoning. The only flavor I git was from the cocktail sauce, which I didn't have enough of so I could eat them all. The catfish poyboy was nothing to be desired. I think the sane flavorless batter was used to fry the catfish. The fries that accompanied the sandwich were the best part of the meal. The peach cobbler was the best part of the meal, very good! The trio of pies were not that desirable. Probably should have sprinkled some sugar and cinnamon on the pies for taste and fried not baked. Baking them had a soft crust instead of a little crisp to it. The highlight of this meal was probably the dessert.

The food was great, from appetizers to dessert. All 4 of us ordered different entrees, and all of us enjoyed our food. The lobster rangoon appetizer was a hit. This is the only place in the DC area we have been able to find Redfish, which is a good Gulf fish. The wait staff is wonderful, very helpful and attentive. The dining area is quite cozy (tight), so I suggest a booth. The front window is usually open and has an oyster bar that serves inside and out. That area can get quite noisy, but we sat in the back by the kitchen entrance and were fine. A little pricy, but food and service were worth it.
